docs/reference/typescript.md
     1Ôćĺ# TypeScript
     2Ôćĺ
     5Ôćĺ## Utilities
     6Ôćĺ
     7Ôćĺ### `Describe`
     8Ôćĺ
     9ÔćĺThe `Describe` utility returns a type representing a struct for a given valid value type. This allows you to ensure you're writing your struct definitions properly, for example:
    10Ôćĺ
    11Ôćĺ```ts
    12Ôćĺtype User = {
    13Ôćĺ  id: number
    14Ôćĺ  name: string
    15Ôćĺ}
    16Ôćĺ
    17Ôćĺconst User: Describe<User> = object({
    18Ôćĺ  id: string(), // This mistake will fail to pass type checking!
    19Ôćĺ  name: string(),
    20Ôćĺ})
    21Ôćĺ```
    22Ôćĺ
    23Ôćĺ> ­čĄľ There are limitations to what `Describe` can do, specifically it will always assume object types are as strict as possible. So describing the `type()` struct is not possible, and simple unions of strings will be required to use `enums()`.
    24Ôćĺ
    25Ôćĺ### `Infer`
    26Ôćĺ
